From: OctaneOS <octaneos@local>
Date: Sat, 12 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] drm: edp: pre-configure audio hardware in encoder_atomic_enable

When EmulationStation takes over KMS on boot, it triggers an
encoder_atomic_disable -> encoder_atomic_enable cycle. The disable path
(drm_edp_output_disable) disables the EDP pixel clock, which resets all
trilinear DP14 controller registers to zero -- including TR_SEC0_AUDIO_ENABLE
(0x900) and the audio config registers (CHANNEL_CNT, MAUD, NAUD, CLOCK_MODE).

PipeWire's PCM substream is already open from its initial startup at this
point. WirePlumber does not close and reopen the PCM on extcon
JACK_VIDEO_OUT PLUGIN -- it keeps the PCM open and re-routes audio.
So audio_startup() is never called again after the register reset,
leaving TR_SEC0_AUDIO_ENABLE=0 and audio dead.

Audio only recovers when the "stop music on screensaver" setting forces
PipeWire to explicitly close the PCM (audio_shutdown), then reopen it on
wake (audio_startup -> hw_params -> full register init).

Confirmed via live /dev/mem reads on hardware:
  before screensaver wake: TR_SEC0_AUDIO_ENABLE=0x00000002 (muted, bit0=0)
  after  screensaver wake: TR_SEC0_AUDIO_ENABLE=0x00000001 (enabled, unmuted)

Fix: after the display link is established in encoder_atomic_enable, directly
pre-configure the EDP audio hardware with 48kHz stereo I2S defaults. This
ensures TR_SEC0_AUDIO_ENABLE and the audio config registers are valid after
the clock-on / link-train sequence, regardless of PipeWire PCM open/close
state. PipeWire hw_params overwrites these with actual negotiated params
when the PCM next cycles normally (e.g. screensaver stop-music + wake).

Signed-off-by: OctaneOS <octaneos@local>
---
 bsp/drivers/drm/sunxi_drm_edp.c | 14 ++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 14 insertions(+)

--- a/bsp/drivers/drm/sunxi_drm_edp.c
+++ b/bsp/drivers/drm/sunxi_drm_edp.c
@@ -3915,8 +3915,22 @@
 
 	/* ensure edp audio always enable after video, avoid display-audio async issue */
 	extcon_set_state_sync(drm_edp->extcon_edp, EXTCON_JACK_VIDEO_OUT, EDP_HPD_PLUGIN);
 
+	/* Pre-configure EDP audio hardware for 48kHz stereo I2S. The
+	 * encoder_atomic_disable→enable cycle (triggered by ES KMS takeover)
+	 * resets all DP14 controller registers to zero via clock gate. PipeWire
+	 * keeps its PCM open across this cycle without re-calling audio_startup,
+	 * so TR_SEC0_AUDIO_ENABLE stays 0 and audio is silent until the PCM
+	 * is fully closed and reopened. Set known-good defaults here so audio
+	 * works immediately after display-enable. PipeWire hw_params overwrites
+	 * these when the PCM next cycles normally (e.g. screensaver wake). */
+	if (drm_edp->source_cap.audio_support) {
+		edp_hw_audio_enable(&drm_edp->edp_hw);
+		edp_hw_audio_config(&drm_edp->edp_hw, HDMI_I2S, 2, 24, 48000);
+		edp_hw_audio_mute(&drm_edp->edp_hw, false, 0);
+	}
+
 	drm_edp->is_enabled = true;
 	return;
 FAIL:
 	DRM_DEBUG_DRIVER("%s fail!\n", __FUNCTION__);
